@node Introduction "SmartTrash - Introduction"
@smartwrap


@{b}Introduction

============@{ub}


  When the Amiga first came out, one of its many revolutionary features was
the use of a trashcan, where "deleted" files were kept in case you later
decided you needed it.


  Ten years on, and the only "improvement" has been a change of icon.


  Many people have tried to improve on the trashcan with an appicon,
allowing you to drag and drop your files, but all the ones I've seen so far
delete the files immediately.  (Thank goodness for DiskSalv!)


  SmartTrash creates an appicon, like the others, but thats where the
similarity ends.  SmartTrash gives the user a second chance, by moving the
files to the trashcan in the root directory.  If the user later realises he
wanted those files, its just a quick trip to the trashcan to dig it out,
rather than a nail biting ten minutes or more, while DiskSalv tries to
recover whats left of your file (if anything).  If the user needs the space,
well, they can click on the trashcan, and select "EMPTY TRASH" from the
menus.

@endnode

@node Features "SmartTrash - Features"
@wordwrap

@{b}Features
========@{ub}

  ░ Configurable APPICON (image, position, legend)
  ░ Accessible from the TOOL menu (optional, configurable Menu item Text)
  ░ Configurable TRASHCAN directory name (e.g. Garbage, WasteBasket etc...)
  ░ Fallback to other trashcan names (e.g. Trashcan, T)
  ░ Automatically create trashcan drawer and icon
  ░ Renames files as "copy_of" if there is already a file by that name.
  ░ Removeable!
  ░ Small!

@endnode

@node Requirements "SmartTrash - Requirements"
@smartwrap


@{b}System Requirements

===================@{ub}


  SmartTrash was developed on a KS3.1 A2000.  It should work on any machine
with KickStart 2 or above, but I've not been able to try it yet.

@endnode

