@node Appendix "Appendix - How the Macintos Wastebasket works"
@smartwrap


@{b}Appendix - How the Macintosh Wastebasket works

==============================================@{ub}


  My first Amiga was an A500, back in the late eighties.  Being a
programmer, I tended to use DELETE if I was using a shell, and the TRASHCAN
if I was working on the Workbench.  I didnt think anything of it, until one
day, one of my mac friends came to me in a ferver and evangelised about how
wonderful the new System Upgrade (system 7 I think) was.  He said that the
best thing was that the Wastebasket was now a @{i}drawer@{ui} so you can
retieve files if you change your mind.  That gave me a jolt.  The Amiga's
trashcan has done that since day one!  What on earth did the mac wastebasket
do before?  He said that it delete files immediately, and considering how
disk intensive macs are, anything deleted is almost complete irretrieveable.


  I spent last summer working as a "multimedia developer", on some macs, and
played with the Wastebasket a bit.  It behaves as a virtual trashcan, in
that it represents the trashcans of all the disks inserted.  If you drag
files to it, they are moved to the trashcan directory in the root of the
disk.  If you double click on it, it opens up a window, containing all the
files in all the trashcans.  You can then drag files in and out of it, or
empty it  with the menu option, deleting all the files from all the
trashcans.


  When all the trashicon style programs appeared, the fact that they DELETED
files made them feel like a step forward, and two steps back.  You might as
well just select delete from the menus.  I resisted using these appicons,
until one day I was looking at some files from a coverdisk.  My workbench
was cluttered with windows.  I selected some files I didnt want, and dragged
them to the trashcan.  The disk whirred.  Nothing.  What was going on?  I
tried a different file, dragged it over, the disk whirred, and it was still
there!  Was I seeing things?  Was I suffering from mouse fatigue?  Was it
an obscure bug in the workbench?  Had I contracted a new and highly
irritating virus?  Nope.  I'd been dragging the files to the WRONG trashcan!
That spurred me into action.


  Incidentally, when you select "LEAVE OUT" from the menus, the Amiga
writes the name to a file called ".backdrop" in the root.  The files are
still physically located where they were before, so you can still run them
if they expect files to be in the same drawer.  On the macs, you have to
drag any extra files they need to the desktop too (more clutter).

@endnode
